# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jim-tracy-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1980-major-league-baseball-season] The **1980 Major League Baseball season** concluded with the Philadelphia Phillies winning their first World Series championship.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1980-major-league-baseball-season] A strike during April 1–8 caused the final eight days of spring training to be canceled, but did not impact the regular season schedule.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1980-major-league-baseball-season] The American League umpires adopted numbers on their uniforms for the first time; National League umpires had numbers on the uniforms since 1970, though the numbers were now white on the blazers and blue on the short-sleeved shirts.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1980-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game, held at Dodger Stadium, saw the National League defeat the American League, 4–2.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1980-major-league-baseball-season] The Phillies finished their regular season with a 91–71 record, defeated the Houston Astros in the 1980 NLCS, and defeated the Kansas City Royals in the 1980 World Series.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1981-major-league-baseball-season] The **1981 Major League Baseball season** culminated with the Los Angeles Dodgers defeating the New York Yankees in the World Series, capturing the franchise's fifth World Series title.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1981-major-league-baseball-season] The season had a players' strike, which lasted from June 12 to July 31, and split the season into two halves.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1981-major-league-baseball-season] Teams that won their division in each half of the season advanced to the playoffs.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1981-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first split season in American League history, and second for the National League, which had played a split season in 1892.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1981-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game was originally scheduled for July 14, but was postponed due to the strike.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1981-major-league-baseball-season] It was ultimately played on August 9, as a prelude to the second half of the season, which began the following day.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1983-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1983 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the 34th season of operation for the league.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1983-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The Pacific League changed their playoff system for the season, which would see the first-place team play the second-place team in a playoff if they finished within five games of each other.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1983-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The system, which never ended up being used in three straight seasons, was discontinued in 1985.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1984 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the 35th season of operation for the league.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The **1994 Major League Baseball season** began on April 3, but ended prematurely on August 11, 1994, with the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The season started despite the expiration of MLB's previous collective bargaining agreement at the end of 1993.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] It was the first season played under the current three-division format in each league.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the first with an Opening Night game involving two National League teams, which did not become permanent until 1996.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] As a result of a players' strike, the MLB season ended prematurely on August 11, 1994.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] No postseason (including the World Series) was played.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Over 260 players were scheduled to exceed $1 million in compensation in 1994.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The Minor League Baseball season was played in its entirety.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] MLB Baseball would not attempt another salary cap until 2026.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of The Baseball Network, the joint venture between MLB, ABC, and NBC.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, ESPN renewed its contract for *Sunday Night Baseball* and *Wednesday Night Baseball*.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Under The Baseball Network's original plan, the All-Star Game would alternate between NBC in even-numbered years and ABC in odd-numbered years.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] After the All-Star Game was complete, ABC took over coverage with what was to be their weekly slate of games under the *Baseball Night in America* banner.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] ABC was scheduled to televise six regular season games on Saturdays or Mondays in prime time.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] NBC would then pick up where ABC left off by televising six more regular season Friday night games.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Every *Baseball Night in America* game was scheduled to begin at 8 p.m.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Pacific Time if the game occurred on the West Coast).
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] A single starting time gave the networks the opportunity to broadcast one game and then, simultaneously, cut to another game when there was a break in action.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The networks had exclusive rights for the twelve regular season dates, in that no regional or national cable service (such as ESPN or superstations like Chicago's WGN-TV or Atlanta's WTBS) or over-the-air broadcaster was allowed to telecast a Major League Baseball game on those dates.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] *Baseball Night in America* (which premiered on July 16, 1994) usually aired up to fourteen games based on the viewers' region (affiliates chose games of local interest to carry) as opposed to a traditional coast-to-coast format.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Normally, announcers who represented each of the teams playing in the respective games were paired with each other.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] More specifically, on regional Saturday night broadcasts and all non-"national" broadcasts, TBN let the two lead announcers from the opposing teams call the games involving their teams together.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Postseason coverage would have also alternated between the two networks.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] In even-numbered years, NBC would have the rights to the All-Star Game and both League Championship Series while ABC would have the World Series and newly created Division Series.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1994-major-league-baseball-season] When the player's strike began on August 12, ABC had only aired games on four of its six scheduled dates, while NBC's slate was supposed to begin on August 26.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The **1998 Major League Baseball season** ended with the New York Yankees sweeping the San Diego Padres in the World Series, after they had won a then AL record 114 regular season games.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees finished with 125 wins for the season (regular season and playoffs combined), which remains the MLB record.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The 1998 season was marked by MLB's expansion to 30 teams (16 in the NL, 14 in the AL), with two new teams–the Arizona Diamondbacks in the National League, and the Tampa Bay Devil Rays in the American League–added.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] To keep the leagues with even numbers of teams while allowing both leagues to have a new team, the Milwaukee Brewers were moved from the American League Central Division to the National League Central Division.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Tigers were shifted from the American League East to the American League Central, while the Devil Rays were added to the American League East.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The Diamondbacks were added to the National League West, making the NL have more teams than the AL for the first time (this arrangement would last until the end of the 2012 season, when the Houston Astros moved from the National to the American League for 2013, giving each league 15 teams).
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The biggest story of the season was the historic chase of the single-season home run record held at the time by Roger Maris.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals' Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr. of the Seattle Mariners started the season on a pace to both break Maris' record.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] In June, the chase was joined by the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa, who broke the decades-old record of Rudy York for most home runs in a calendar month with 20 that month.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] Eventually, Griffey fell off the record pace, but still ended with 56 homers.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] Both McGwire and Sosa broke the record in September, with McGwire ultimately finishing with 70 homers to Sosa's 66.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] McGwire's record would last only three years, with Barry Bonds hitting 73 in 2001.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The 1998 season was also the first in MLB history with four players hitting 50 or more homers, with Greg Vaughn of the San Diego Padres hitting 50.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] In a postscript to the record chase, both McGwire and Sosa have since been widely accused of having used performance-enhancing drugs during that period, and McGwire would admit in 2010 that he had used steroids during the record-setting season.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] The defending World Series champions Florida Marlins finished last in the NL East Division at 54–108, making it the first, and only, time that a team went from winning the World Series one year to finishing with 100 or more losses and last in their division the following year.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] On July 9, 1998, Major League Baseball Executive Council chairman Bud Selig officially became the 9th commissioner of baseball, though he had been the de facto commissioner for nearly 6 years.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] During that time, the owners had tried to find a replacement for previous commissioner Fay Vincent who was forced to step down by the owners towards the end of 1992 season mainly due to the lockout he intervened in during the 1990 season.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season in which teams were seeded by their respective win–loss record within their respective leagues.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third season under the five-year rights agreements with ESPN, Fox, and NBC.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] ESPN continued to air *Sunday Night Baseball* and *Wednesday Night Baseball*.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] Fox's coverage included *Fox Saturday Baseball* broadcasts, Thursday night games on Fox Sports Net, and Saturday primetime games on FX.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] During the postseason, ESPN, Fox, and NBC split the four Division Series.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1998-major-league-baseball-season] NBC then televised the American League Championship Series while Fox aired both the National League Championship Series and the World Series.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] The **1999 Major League Baseball season** ended with the New York Yankees sweeping the Atlanta Braves in the World Series.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] The previous record of most home runs hit in a season, set at 5,064 in 1998, was broken once again as the American League and National League combined to hit 5,528 home runs.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] Moreover, it was the first season in 49 years to feature a team that scored 1,000 runs in a season, as the Cleveland Indians led the Majors with 1,009 runs scored.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] Only 193 shutouts were recorded in 2,427 regular-season games.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] The 1999 season was the first season in which the two current New York City-area MLB teams, the Yankees and Mets, qualified for the playoffs together in the same season.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] The following season, both teams reached the World Series and the Yankees won four games to one.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Two teams in the same division could not meet in the division series.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] This was the fourth season under the five-year rights agreements with ESPN, Fox, and NBC.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] Fox's coverage included *Fox Saturday Baseball* broadcasts, Thursday night games on Fox Sports Net, Saturday primetime games on FX, and the All-Star Game.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/1999-major-league-baseball-season] Fox then televised the American League Championship Series while NBC aired both the National League Championship Series and the World Series.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy was an All-America baseball player at Marietta College, an NCAA Division III institution in Ohio.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] In 1976, he played collegiate summer baseball with the Chatham A's of the Cape Cod Baseball League and was named a league all-star.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] He played as an outfielder for parts of two seasons with the Chicago Cubs in 1980–81.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] He also played two seasons in Japan with the Yokohama Taiyo Whales in 1983–84.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy worked as a minor league manager for several organizations including the Ottawa Lynx in 1994.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] He is featured as the manager of the 1988 Peoria Chiefs in the book "The Boys Who Would Be Cubs", by Joseph Bosco .
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy later served as the bench coach of the Montreal Expos (under manager Felipe Alou), and the Dodgers (under manager Davey Johnson) in 1999 and 2000.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy was manager of the Los Angeles Dodgers from 2001 to 2005, compiling four winning seasons and a 427–383 record.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] With Tracy as manager, the Dodgers won the National League West division in 2004 but lost 3-1 to the St.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Louis Cardinals in the National League Division Series.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy was hired by the Pittsburgh Pirates on October 11, 2005.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] In two disappointing seasons in Pittsburgh, he compiled a 135–189 record.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy was fired by the Pirates on October 5, 2007.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy was hired as bench coach for the Colorado Rockies in November 2008.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] On May 29, 2009, Clint Hurdle was fired with an 18–28 record, and Tracy was named to replace him.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy led the Rockies to the postseason, with a 74–42 (.638) record after taking over as manager, but lost the NLDS to the Philadelphia Phillies by a score of 3 games to 1.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] For his efforts in the 2009 season, Tracy won the National League Manager of the Year Award as voted on by the Baseball Writers' Association of America.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] He was also named the NL Manager of the Year by *The Sporting News*.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] On November 19, 2009, Tracy was rewarded with a three-year contract extension.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] In 2010, the Rockies lost 13 of their last 14 games, collapsing from a 1⁄2 game deficit in the wild card race to finish 8 games behind an Atlanta Braves team that went 6-8 in the same span.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] In 2011, the Rockies began the season with an 11-2 record before finishing the season with a 62-87 (.416) run that landed them in 4th place.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] After the 2011 season, the Rockies rewarded Tracy with an "indefinite" contract extension.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] The Rockies went on to accumulate a 37-65 record (.363) through August 1, leading to a front office reshuffle that left Jim Tracy and his staff intact.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy resigned as manager of the Rockies on October 7, 2012, following a disappointing and injury plagued 2012 season that saw the Rockies finish 64-98, the 2nd worst record in franchise history.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] In 2003, Tracy was in the audience during a taping of *The Price Is Right* and was introduced to the crowd by host Bob Barker.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Tracy's oldest son, Brian, played baseball at UC Santa Barbara, and was drafted in 2007 by the Pirates.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Brian later became a scout for the Pirates.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Middle son Chad played in the minor leagues for eight seasons, including four seasons in Triple-A for three different franchises, and went on to manage in the minor leagues.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] In April 2026, Chad was announced as the interim manager of the Boston Red Sox.
[src:jim-tracy-baseball/jim-tracy-baseball] Youngest son Mark also played minor league baseball from 2010 to 2013.
